      "chunks": [
        {
          "text": "Recent advancements have shifted the focus toward developing and assessing scientific agents in accelerating scientific research. New benchmarks span the full research pipeline:\n(1) Scientific Ideation: Evaluates agents’ ability to generate novel, expert-level research ideas, emphasizing creativity, relevance, and scientific feasibility Si et al. ( [2025](https://arxiv.org/html/2503.16416v2#bib.bib168 \"Can LLMs generate novel research ideas? a large-scale human study with 100+ NLP researchers\")).\n(2) Experiment Design: Benchmark",
          "charCount": 534
        },
        {
          "text": "For episodic memory evaluation, Huet et al. ( [2025](https://arxiv.org/html/2503.16416v2#bib.bib10 \"Episodic memories generation and evaluation benchmark for large language models\")) proposes a specialized benchmark to assess how LLMs generate and manage memories that capture specific events with contextual details. This benchmark utilizes synthetically created book chapters and events with LLMs-based judge evaluation metrics to measure accuracy and relevance.\nStreamBench Wu et al. ( [2024a](https://arxiv.org/html/2503.16416v2#b",
          "charCount": 534
        },
        {
          "text": "Recently, research agents at the intersection of search, web, and scientific agents have become common, due to a wide commercial offering. Such agents retrieve and synthesize information before returning comprehensive citation-backed answers. This process poses a difficult\nevaluation task with multi-step, multi-faceted, time-insensitive consideration.\nPatel et al. ( [2025](https://arxiv.org/html/2503.16416v2#bib.bib229 \"DeepScholar-bench: a live benchmark and automated evaluation for generative research synthesis\")) proposed e",
