        {
          "text": "Most benchmarks come with a set of “ **ground truth**” answers to compare against, though alternative evaluation methods exist, like Chatbot Arena, which uses crowdsourced human labels. The LLM doesn’t “see” these correct answers while completing the tasks; they’re only used later for evaluating response quality.",
          "charCount": 314
        },
        {
          "text": "- **Overlap-based metrics** like BLEU and ROUGE **.** They are used for tasks like translation or free-form responses, where various phrasing options are valid, and an exact match is rare. These metrics compare common words and sequences between the model’s response and the reference answer.\n- **Functional code quality.** Some coding benchmarks, like HumanEval, use unique metrics such as pass@k, which reflects how many generated code samples pass unit tests for given problems.\n- **Fine-tuned evaluator models.** The TruthfulQA be",
          "charCount": 534
        },
        {
          "text": "[Humanity's Last Exam](https://github.com/centerforaisafety/hle) is a multi-modal benchmark created to push LLMs closer to expert-level human reasoning and knowledge. It consists of 2,500 questions across dozens of subjects, including mathematics, humanities, and the natural sciences. Questions were filtered to avoid ones easily answered via web search or prompt-memorization. Currently, even very strong LLMs  achieve relatively low accuracy on HLE, suggesting there's still a large gap between AI and human expert performance on d",
          "charCount": 534
        }
      ]
