      "chunks": [
        {
          "text": "[Sign in](https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2F%40lmpo%2Fllm-evaluation-benchmarks-vs-human-judgment-f1cdd16098c0&source=post_page---top_nav_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav------------------)",
          "charCount": 246
        },
        {
          "text": "How do we know which AI model is “best”? It’s a simple question that often leads to a complex answer. We see leaderboards, benchmarks, and scores that seem to offer a clear ranking, but the reality of how these models are evaluated is far more nuanced. The most common methods for grading Large Language Models (LLMs) have surprising limitations that aren’t immediately obvious from a quick glance at a chart. This article peels back the curtain on LLM evaluation. To understand these truths, it helps to know that evaluation methods ",
          "charCount": 534
        },
        {
          "text": "Benchmark-based evaluation provides a quantitative way to assess an LLM’s **factual recall** or **task-solving ability**. It’s akin to giving the model a standardized exam — with a set of right and wrong answers.",
          "charCount": 212
        }
      ]
