        "statusCode": 200
      },
      "chunks": [
        {
          "text": "- **LLM metrics** measures output quality across dimensions like correctness and relevance.\n- **Common mistakes**: relying on traditional scorers like BLEU/ROUGE, where semantic nuance in LLM outputs is not captured.\n- **LLM-as-a-judge** is the most reliable method—using an LLM to evaluate with natural language rubrics, but requires various techniques like G-Eval.\n- **Evaluation metrics** in the context of LLM evaluation can be categorized as either **single or multi-turn**, targeting end-to-end LLM systems or at a component-lev",
          "charCount": 534
        },
        {
          "text": "LLM evaluation metrics such as answer correctness, semantic similarity, and hallucination, are metrics that score an LLM system's output based on criteria you care about. They are critical to LLM evaluation, as they help quantify the performance of different LLM systems, **which can just be the LLM itself.**",
          "charCount": 309
        },
        {
          "text": "1. **Answer Relevancy:** Determines whether an LLM output is able to address the given input in an informative and concise manner.\n2. **Task Completion:** Determines whether an LLM agent is able to complete the task it was set out to do.\n3. **Correctness:** Determines whether an LLM output is factually correct based on some ground truth.\n4. **Hallucination:** Determines whether an LLM output contains fake or made-up information.\n5. **Tool Correctness:** Determines whether an LLM agent is able to call the correct tools for a give",
          "charCount": 534
        }
